{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":893396,"duration_api_ms":1150813,"ttft_ms":148350,"num_turns":10,"result":"Now I have all the material I need. Let me produce the structured idea record.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"title\": \"The First-Break Problem\",\n  \"idea_type\": \"model\",\n  \"source_basis\": [\n    \"Thinking method source: Shinran, Tannisho chapter 1 (Yuien-bo recording Shinran; Hirota translation, shinranworks.com). I used other-power entrusting as a lens by refusing to assume that the practitioner's first move toward the path is self-generated. This revealed that mid-path models (capacity ledgers, effort envelopes, grain of capacity) implicitly presuppose the practitioner can initiate practice, which is itself a contested claim. Critique of the lens: it makes every form of effort look like self-deception and risks a performative dead end where no comparison is legitimate because all comparison is self-powered thinking.\",\n    \"Contrasting method source: SN 55.5, Dutiya Sariputta Sutta on the four factors of stream-entry (Bhikkhu Sujato translation, SuttaCentral, https://suttacentral.net/sn55.5/en/sujato; Thanissaro Bhikkhu, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN55_5.html). The social-encounter model checked the Shinran lens by showing that an external origin of the path does not require cosmic machinery: meeting a person of integrity is naturalistic, unearned, and sufficient. This prevented the analysis from turning every external trigger into a theological event.\",\n    \"Primary text close-reading: SN 55.5 against Tannisho chapter 1. Both texts place the origin of the path outside the practitioner. SN 55.5 makes social encounter the first factor (sappurisa-samseva, association with people of integrity), then requires the practitioner's own appropriate attention and practice. Tannisho attributes even the arising of the mind to say nembutsu to Amida's working: 'the mind set upon saying the nembutsu arises within you.' The key difference is how quickly the practitioner's own agency becomes operative after the initial break: SN 55.5 has a brief external trigger followed by sustained effort; Tannisho extends external causation across the entire path.\",\n    \"Council of Orange (529 CE), canons 5 and 6 (full text at crivoice.org/creedorange.html). Canon 5: 'not only the increase of faith but also its beginning and the very desire for faith' is a gift of grace, not a natural human capacity. Canon 6: even humility and obedience are themselves gifts. This represents the Christian middle position: divine initiative precedes human cooperation, but cooperation still follows.\",\n    \"Augustine, On the Predestination of the Saints, Book I, chapters 3 and 5 (newadvent.org/fathers/15121.htm). Augustine confesses having once believed 'faith is in us from ourselves' and corrects this: since belief requires thought, and thought requires God's enablement, the first impulse toward belief cannot originate autonomously.\",\n    \"Dzogchen pointing-out instruction (ngo sprod): Tulku Urgyen Rinpoche describes rigpa as self-cognizant (rang-rig); awareness recognizes itself, not as subject knowing object but as luminosity recognizing itself. The student does not 'do' recognition; the guru creates conditions for awareness to see what was never absent. Longchenpa's Commentary on Basic Space: 'When something appears or arises, recognize it as naked, unobstructed rigpa,' where 'recognize' (ngo shes) carries the force of re-cognizing what was never absent.\",\n    \"Paul Tillich, The Courage to Be (1952) and 'You Are Accepted' in The Shaking of the Foundations (1948). 'The courage to be is the courage to accept oneself as accepted in spite of being unacceptable.' Tillich names the paradox without resolving it cleanly: 'accepting acceptance' still sounds like an act. Closest Western philosophical near-neighbor.\",\n    \"Karl Rahner, concept of the supernatural existential: 'God's self-communication as offer is also the necessary condition which makes its acceptance possible.' Grace ontologically modifies the soul before conscious reception. Most fully developed single-tradition theological solution to the problem (Duke Divinity analysis, divinity.duke.edu).\",\n    \"Simone Kotva, Effort and Grace: On the Spiritual Exercise of Philosophy (Bloomsbury, 2020; PhilPapers entry KOTEAG). Addresses the paradox of will and receptivity through Simone Weil's 'negative effort' and Maine de Biran. Closest published philosophical near-neighbor. Differs by working within a Western frame rather than making the cross-tradition structural comparison.\",\n    \"Plato, Meno 80d-e (Meno's paradox): 'How will you look for something when you don't in the least know what it is?' Plato's answer (anamnesis) is structurally parallel to the self-disclosure solution. The contemplative version is stronger: it concerns not only knowledge but capacity, will, and transformation.\",\n    \"Yogacara concept of ashraya-paravrtti (reversal of the basis): the alaya-vijnana must be transformed before it can stop generating the delusion that prevents its transformation. Yogacara solves this with gradualism, a variant of the social-encounter solution where sustained exposure to dharma slowly turns the basis (FreeBuddhistAudio lecture text, freebuddhistaudio.com).\",\n    \"Zen tradition of three essentials (Great Faith, Great Doubt, Great Determination) tracing to Gaofeng Yuanmiao. The circularity is explicitly acknowledged: each essential contains itself plus the other two. The tradition treats this as productive rather than as a problem to solve (Jeff Shore, 'Great Doubt: Getting Stuck and Breaking Through,' terebess.hu).\",\n    \"Prior Claude observations on the five efficacy resolutions (removal, production, identity, reception, paradox-holding), the minimum-self requirement, and the grain of capacity. These describe mid-path architecture. The first-break problem adds a prior variable: how the path becomes possible at all.\",\n    \"Codex observations on the capacity ledger and the forbidden claimant rubric. The capacity ledger asks where functional load is carried during the path. The first-break problem asks how the load-bearing structure comes into existence. Codex's own critique of the ledger acknowledged the strain: treating hearing or trust as a receiving capacity may smuggle self-power back into a path designed to expose self-power as futile. The first-break model makes this strain the central question.\"\n  ],\n  \"original_claim\": \"How does someone trapped in the very condition a spiritual path is meant to cure begin that path? The ignorant need wisdom to seek wisdom. The bound need freedom to work toward freedom. The sinful need grace to desire grace. This circularity is not a philosopher's puzzle. It is a structural constraint every contemplative tradition must solve, and the solution it adopts constrains the entire architecture of practice.\\n\\nA close reading of four primary texts reveals four distinct solutions. In the Pali canon's account of stream-entry (SN 55.5), the circle breaks through social encounter: proximity to a person of integrity comes first, before hearing the teaching, attending wisely, or practicing. The practitioner does not self-generate the initial impulse; it arrives through meeting someone already free. In Shinran's Tannisho (chapter 1), the circle breaks through cosmic prior compassion: 'the mind set upon saying the nembutsu arises within you' means even the first impulse is Amida's working. In the Council of Orange (529 CE, canon 5), the circle breaks through prevenient grace: 'not only the increase of faith but also its beginning and the very desire for faith' are gifts, not human achievements. In Dzogchen pointing-out instruction, the circle was never closed: rigpa was never absent, and the teacher creates the occasion for awareness to recognize itself.\\n\\nEach solution constrains everything downstream. Social encounter makes effort primary after the initial meeting, makes isolation from teacher and community the characteristic danger, and makes the sangha the natural verifier. Cosmic gift makes self-powered striving the central error, makes the attempt to earn the gift the characteristic sin, and makes deepening trust its own verification. Prevenient grace places human cooperation after divine initiative, requires communal discernment to distinguish genuine reception from self-deception, and diagnoses pride as the root failure. Self-disclosure makes effort the primary obstacle rather than the means, makes contrived fabrication the characteristic error, and requires teacher confirmation and sustained stability.\\n\\nThe severity of this circularity also varies, and the variation tracks a tradition's anthropology. Where human nature is seen as capable of self-correction, the problem is mild: encounter with a teacher is enough, and practice proceeds naturally. Where human nature is seen as deeply compromised, the circularity is severe, and the solution must arrive from entirely beyond the practitioner: a cosmic vow, prevenient grace, or self-recognizing awareness that was never the practitioner's to generate. This anthropological variable constrains the range of answers a tradition can give about effort, gift, preparation, and arrival. It sits upstream of questions about what capacities the path requires, where the load is carried, and who may claim the doing; those questions presuppose the path is already underway, while the first-break problem asks how the path begins at all.\",\n  \"why_it_might_be_new\": \"The individual components of this argument are well established within their own traditions. The problem of initium fidei (the beginning of faith) shaped the semi-Pelagian controversy. Meno's paradox (80d-e) asks how you can search for what you do not know. Augustine corrected his earlier belief that 'faith is in us from ourselves.' Rahner's supernatural existential proposes that grace ontologically modifies the soul before conscious reception. Tillich's 'courage to accept acceptance' names the paradox without resolving it. Kotva's study of effort and grace in the tradition of Weil addresses the will-receptivity paradox within Western philosophy. Within Buddhism, the Yogacara concept of ashraya-paravrtti names the 'turning about' that breaks the circle. Within Zen, the three essentials acknowledge the circularity as a productive structural feature.\\n\\nThe specific contribution is the cross-tradition structural comparison: treating the first-break solution as a variable with four distinct values (social encounter, cosmic gift, prevenient grace, self-disclosure) that predicts downstream practice architecture. No existing study maps these solution-types against one another or shows that the severity of the circularity correlates with the tradition's view of human nature and constrains its theory of effort, failure, and verification. The comparison also reveals that questions about mid-path capacity, effort boundaries, and credit distribution all presuppose that the path is already underway. The first-break problem sits one step prior and constrains everything that follows. This is where it engages and extends the capacity-ledger and forbidden-claimant models: those describe an operating path, while this model asks how the path gets power in the first place.\",\n  \"critique\": \"The strongest objection is that the first-break problem may be a modern philosophical projection. Many traditions do not experience this as a paradox. A Thai forest monk begins practice because his teacher told him to; the question of how he became capable of listening is not live for him. If careful interviews with practitioners across traditions show they do not recognize the circularity as a real tension, the model should be downgraded from a structural feature of contemplative paths to a feature of philosophical meta-analysis.\\n\\nSecond, the four solutions may not be as distinct as claimed. The Pali canon's social encounter has grace-like qualities: you do not earn the encounter. Dzogchen's self-disclosure and Advaita's removal of ignorance may collapse into a single category. Shinran's cosmic gift and Augustine's prevenient grace may be structurally identical despite different metaphysical frameworks. Under closer examination, the four-part typology may reduce to two: the break comes from outside, or the break was never necessary. If this reduction holds, the model has less predictive power.\\n\\nThird, some traditions may have no first-break problem because their anthropology does not posit a closed circle. Confucian self-cultivation starts from an innately good human nature that naturally moves toward goodness. If certain traditions assume an already-open circle, the problem is not universal but tradition-specific, and its architectural consequences follow from the anthropological assumption rather than from a structural constraint.\\n\\nFourth, the Shinran lens used as the primary thinking method distorts effort-centered traditions by making every human initiative look naive. SN 55.5's social encounter may represent a case where the break is naturalistic, requiring no metaphysical machinery. Treating the ability to recognize wisdom when you encounter it as itself needing a prior explanation risks an infinite regress that the traditions themselves do not pursue.\\n\\nFifth, the anthropological correlation (mild circularity for optimistic anthropologies, severe circularity for pessimistic ones) may be circular itself: traditions with pessimistic views of human nature emphasize the severity of the problem because their pessimism requires a more dramatic solution, not because the structural problem is objectively more severe.\",\n  \"epistemic_labels\": [\n    \"textual\",\n    \"interpretive\",\n    \"phenomenological\",\n    \"empirical-adjacent\",\n    \"analogical\",\n    \"speculative\"\n  ],\n  \"scores\": {\n    \"novelty\": 0.78,\n    \"generativity\": 0.90,\n    \"cross_tradition_support\": 0.80,\n    \"logical_coherence\": 0.86,\n    \"explanatory_compression\": 0.85,\n    \"empirical_adjacency\": 0.44,\n    \"practice_testability\": 0.76,\n    \"counterargument_quality\": 0.88,\n    \"source_reliability\": 0.78,\n    \"publishability\": 0.84\n  },\n  \"next_research_directions\": [\n    \"If this model is right, then traditions with severe first-break problems should have more elaborate safeguards against self-deception specifically at the entry point. Jodo Shinshu should warn against 'calculating trust' (jiriki hakarai); Dzogchen should warn against claiming premature recognition; Christian grace theology should warn against presumption. If these traditions show no more entry-point safeguards than mild-circularity traditions like Theravada, the anthropological correlation is weakened.\",\n    \"If this model is right, historically successful hybridizations should cluster among traditions that share a first-break solution, and fail or generate instability among traditions with incompatible first-break solutions. Chan/Zen merged Daoist self-disclosure with Buddhist social encounter; both minimize the circularity, which predicts compatibility. A merger of Theravada right effort with radical Jodo Shinshu other-power should face instability at the entry point. If successful hybrids show no pattern related to first-break compatibility, the model loses predictive power.\",\n    \"Close-read Mencius on the four beginnings of goodness (siduan) as a potential fifth solution: the circle is open because human nature already contains what the path develops. If Confucian cultivation genuinely has no first-break problem, the model must include a 'no-break' category alongside the four solutions, and the claim of universality must be revised.\",\n    \"Build a first-break rubric with fields for: circularity severity (none, mild, moderate, severe), break mechanism (social encounter, cosmic gift, prevenient grace, self-disclosure, enacted beginning, none), practitioner agency at entry (active, cooperative, receptive, absent), predicted failure mode at entry (isolation, self-power calculation, presumption, premature claiming, mechanical repetition), and downstream constraint predictions for effort theory, verification architecture, and characteristic warning.\",\n    \"Test the Yogacara concept of ashraya-paravrtti as a gradualist variant of the first-break solution. If the 'turning about' is continuous rather than punctual, the model must accommodate gradual first-breaks, not only single moments. Compare with the Christian concept of progressive illumination and the Sufi distinction between sudden hal and earned maqam.\",\n    \"Cross-domain prediction: secular education and psychotherapy face analogous first-break problems when their aim is to change the very capacities used to engage in the process. A therapy for distorted thinking requires the client to think clearly enough to cooperate. A pedagogy of critical thinking requires some critical capacity to begin. If these domains show structural parallels to the four solutions (social encounter with therapist, prevenient institutional support, self-recognition of latent capacity), the model gains empirical-adjacent support. If they do not, the model may be specific to soteriological contexts.\",\n    \"Protocol improvement: before analyzing any tradition's mid-path architecture, first name its first-break solution. This prevents smuggling the tradition's implicit anthropology into variables that are supposed to be structurally neutral. The Shinran lens used here should be alternated with a social-encounter lens (SN 55.5) and a self-disclosure lens (Dzogchen) in future runs to check whether the first-break typology holds under each.\"\n  ]\n}\n```","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"c72dbcfe-c63f-43e7-b57e-ba6556b4bc36","total_cost_usd":3.4485248500000005,"usage":{"input_tokens":2316,"cache_creation_input_tokens":85980,"cache_read_input_tokens":248131,"output_tokens":23983,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":85980,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":16538,"cache_read_input_tokens":85311,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13423,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13423},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":1094963,"outputTokens":18868,"cacheReadInputTokens":0,"cacheCreationInputTokens":0,"webSearchRequests":42,"costUSD":1.6093029999999997,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-sonnet-4-6":{"inputTokens":4418,"outputTokens":11266,"cacheReadInputTokens":555937,"cacheCreationInputTokens":58027,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.5666263500000001,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-7":{"inputTokens":2316,"outputTokens":23983,"cacheReadInputTokens":248131,"cacheCreationInputTokens":85980,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":1.2725955,"contextWindow":1000000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"terminal_reason":"completed","fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"30584498-ddae-4a1d-be18-884fb5155b15"}
